      "id": "af466bc29a8c6b3c",
      "text": "The third point, namely the change of simultaneity, was the most fundamental one. Two clocks together (call them A and B) would both slow down if running together. But if one was slowly separated from the other and then brought back to the same velocity, you would see that the two clocks were out of phase from one another. While separating, the second clock B is going more slowly than the first clock A. Thus, A and B get out of phase. They no longer register the same time. If you brought them back together, they would, however, get back in phase."
